<title type="html"><![CDATA[Emulation accuracy level]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5797&amp;p=53647#p53647"><![CDATA[
When testing for defects in the parts of a program that do I/O (usually the video or sound code), I care about accuracy because my program is unknown.<br /><br />But once I know a program's I/O is solid, I start testing for game logic defects or balance. At that point, I start to care more about ways I can sacrifice accuracy in obscure cases to gain speed accuracy while retaining compatibility. When play-testing things on the city bus, I'll even turn on PocketNES's PPU hack and auto speed hack (e.g. BEQ skipping or BVC skipping) because it makes the speed more accurate.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sun Dec 06, 2009 7:20 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
