<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5797&amp;p=53636#p53636</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5797&amp;p=53636#p53636"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Emulation accuracy level]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5797&amp;p=53636#p53636"><![CDATA[
- Well, I'd like to setup a few things regarding the accuracy of a NES emulator, please, changes and suggestions are welcome.<br /><br />0. The emulator must emulate the CPU, even if the PPU displays nothing or a distorted image, meaning color attribute problems or even a wrong tile arrangement.<br /><br />1. The PPU output must be clean, using right attribute colors, palette and "decent" scrolling. The "decent" means proper emulation of sprite 0 hits, but not rastering effects/splits with IRQs.<br /><br />2. The APU unit must be emulated correctly, the proper I/O registers behavior. Sound output isn't required for this level.<br /><br />3. All the 3 units work OK and pass through a test suite (PPU, CPU and APU). The sound output is still optional, much like the PPU video output filtering.<br /><br />4a. PPU timing is accurate, meaning the VBlank, NMI and sprite 0 hit timings.<br />4b. APU timing is accurate, meaning the 4 or 5 steps + 4017h register.<br /><br />5. Mapper IRQs work with no major problems. Glitching is allowed if occurs in the NES hardware.<br /><br />- Well, as comparision, NESticle is at level 2. ^_^;;<br />- You can say that emulator X is inaccurate only if it's on level 0 or 1, but partially accurate from level 2. I'd say "accurate" at level 3, and "perfectly accurate" at level 4, since 5 looks "optional".<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=39">Zepper</a> — Sun Dec 06, 2009 3:36 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
